WEBVTT

00:26.318 --> 00:29.613
<i>ERNIE: 21 straight lines,
five yards apart,</i>

00:29.988 --> 00:31.740
<i>that's a football field.</i>

00:31.823 --> 00:34.451
<i>But there are other lines,
ones you don't see,</i>

00:34.534 --> 00:38.205
<i>that run deeper and wider,
all the way through a country,</i>

00:38.789 --> 00:40.916
<i>and aren't part of any game.</i>

00:47.005 --> 00:49.591
SARETTE: Strong load
right, 42 shovel pass.
On one. On one.

00:49.675 --> 00:51.176
Ready?
ALL: Break!

00:56.265 --> 00:58.850
SARETTE: Whiskey, whiskey, 33!

00:59.685 --> 01:01.853
Been waiting
for this, spook.

01:05.482 --> 01:07.484
I'm gonna kick your black
ass back to Africa, boy.

01:15.492 --> 01:17.035
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

01:51.403 --> 01:54.197
(STAMMERING)
I found another Pepsi.

01:56.908 --> 01:59.619
(SINGING) <i>Pepsi Cola
hits the spot</i>

01:59.745 --> 02:02.622
<i>12 full ounces,
that's a lot</i>
<i>12 full ounces,
that's a lot</i>

02:02.748 --> 02:05.751
<i>Twice as much
for a nickel, too</i>
<i>Twice as much
for a nickel, too</i>

02:05.876 --> 02:08.294
<i>Pepsi Cola is
the drink for you</i>
<i>Pepsi Cola is
the drink for you</i>

02:11.548 --> 02:16.470
<i>MALE NARRATOR 1: America has
been riding the crest of a
wave of a peaceful prosperity.</i>

02:17.763 --> 02:20.140
<i>MALE NARRATOR 2: I believe
in this world to come.</i>

02:20.432 --> 02:23.352
<i>/ think it's going to
be a pretty good one.</i>

02:40.786 --> 02:42.454
"When you say 'Budweiser,'

02:42.537 --> 02:45.457
"you've said it all."
"You've said it all."

02:54.299 --> 02:57.302
What are you boys doing
north of Union Street?

03:00.138 --> 03:02.182
One of you better answer.

03:02.474 --> 03:03.934
Just collecting bottles.

03:04.017 --> 03:06.186
These are our
bottles up here.

03:06.269 --> 03:08.063
(TRAIN HORN BLOWING)

03:08.146 --> 03:09.564
Hey, guys!

03:10.482 --> 03:12.567
(TRAIN APPROACHING)

03:20.617 --> 03:22.911
Ain't but one
thing to do here.

03:23.995 --> 03:26.123
Ernie, you
listening to me?

03:27.499 --> 03:29.000
Ernie, now!

03:32.421 --> 03:34.089
Ernie!

03:34.172 --> 03:35.424
(ALL LAUGHING)

03:35.841 --> 03:39.344
Ernie! Ernie!

03:39.553 --> 03:41.513
This one must be stupid.

03:44.391 --> 03:47.310
I'll tell you what,
you give us those bottles

03:47.394 --> 03:49.813
and we won't
kick your black ass.

03:50.355 --> 03:52.566
(STAMMERING)

03:54.192 --> 03:56.027
(ALL LAUGHING)

03:57.362 --> 03:59.990
Got something to say?

04:00.574 --> 04:02.033
No!

04:02.367 --> 04:03.326
What?

04:03.410 --> 04:05.829
Not only stupid,
but retarded.

04:06.204 --> 04:08.457
And a nigger,
how sad is that?

04:09.249 --> 04:12.669
Look, you've got
three seconds to
drop those bottles.

04:15.005 --> 04:16.173
One,

04:20.385 --> 04:21.595
two,

04:24.389 --> 04:25.599
three!

04:27.726 --> 04:29.436
Get him.
Get him.

04:29.519 --> 04:30.729
(GRUNTS)

04:34.399 --> 04:36.193
(ALL SHOUTING)

04:45.035 --> 04:48.663
<i>ERNIE: Dear Mr. Martin,
it feels strange to
write about my life.</i>

04:49.873 --> 04:53.835
<i>/ can't tell you the exact
moment I knew what it was
I wanted to be</i>

04:53.919 --> 04:56.379
<i>or how I wanted
to make my mark.</i>

04:56.463 --> 04:59.007
<i>Maybe it just felt
real good to run,</i>

04:59.090 --> 05:01.468
<i>or maybe one day,</i>
<i>out of the corner of my eye,</i>

05:01.551 --> 05:05.138
<i>/ saw tacklers
reaching out for me
and dropping behind.</i>

05:06.515 --> 05:11.394
<i>Back in 1949,</i>
<i>at the age of 10,</i>
<i>one thing I did know was,</i>

05:12.479 --> 05:16.066
<i>/ sure didn't</i>
<i>want to be remembered
for running too slow.</i>

05:20.195 --> 05:23.907
<i>People in town
would always ask,
"What you running from?"</i>

05:23.990 --> 05:25.033
ERNIE: Hey, Will!

05:25.116 --> 05:27.452
<i>/ didn't know</i>
<i>then what I know now,</i>

05:27.536 --> 05:30.830
<i>that I wasn't running from,
I was running to.</i>

05:32.541 --> 05:35.377
POPS: After dinner
we gonna have an ice
cream eating contest.

05:35.460 --> 05:36.461
What do you
say about that?

05:36.545 --> 05:38.296
Yeah, I like it.

05:39.130 --> 05:40.257
POPS: Okay.

05:41.925 --> 05:45.512
First Corinthians 15:10.

05:45.971 --> 05:47.013
Ernie.

05:47.097 --> 05:48.557
Yes, Grandpa.

05:48.640 --> 05:50.809
Why don't you read tonight?

05:52.811 --> 05:54.020
(SIGHS)

05:55.230 --> 05:56.773
POPS: You can do it.

05:58.858 --> 06:00.318
(STAMMERING) "But

06:02.529 --> 06:04.823
"by the..."

06:07.951 --> 06:11.204
Ernie, take a deep breath.

06:12.330 --> 06:13.373
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

06:13.456 --> 06:16.251
Okay, now try it again.

06:19.504 --> 06:22.924
"But by the

06:24.217 --> 06:27.637
"grace of God I am what I am.

06:29.055 --> 06:30.265
"And his grace...

06:30.348 --> 06:31.558
POPS: "His grace...

06:31.641 --> 06:32.601
"...which was bestowed..."

06:32.684 --> 06:34.561
"...which was
bestowed
upon me

06:34.644 --> 06:36.521
"was not in vain."

06:41.109 --> 06:43.945
"But I labored
more abundantly
than they all,

06:44.529 --> 06:45.947
"yet not I,

06:47.699 --> 06:50.535
"but the grace of
God which was with me."

06:51.286 --> 06:54.289
The words, I know
they're in there

06:54.372 --> 06:57.584
but they don't come out
straight all the time.

07:05.925 --> 07:07.260
<i>ANNOUNCER: That'll bring
Jackie Robinson up.</i>

07:07.344 --> 07:10.096
He's wearing
a Brooklyn
Dodgers uniform.

07:10.555 --> 07:13.224
He's Negro
and he's playing for
the Brooklyn Dodgers?

07:13.308 --> 07:17.771
That's right, boys.
That there is
Jackie Robinson.

07:18.938 --> 07:21.107
<i>ANNOUNCER: The windup
and the delivery.</i>

07:21.566 --> 07:26.029
<i>And the drive
deep into left field.
And it's a home run!</i>

07:30.909 --> 07:35.163
<i>Jackie Robinson
with a home run,
his 12th of the year,</i>

07:35.246 --> 07:37.707
<i>and the crowd
roars at Ebbets Field.</i>

07:44.673 --> 07:47.634
Now what? You gonna
stare at it all night?

07:48.510 --> 07:51.262
This here is a man
who's doing a lot

07:51.930 --> 07:52.931
without saying nothing.

07:53.014 --> 07:55.308
(SCHOOL BELL RINGING)

07:59.145 --> 08:01.022
Hey!
Hey, Ernie.

08:03.733 --> 08:04.943
Ernie!

08:07.862 --> 08:09.072
Mama?

08:11.950 --> 08:13.159
Mama!

08:13.243 --> 08:15.537
(EXCLAIMING)

08:17.122 --> 08:18.164
<i>WILL: It's great
to have you back!</i>

08:18.248 --> 08:20.166
So you still got
that Chevy? And
what year is that?

08:20.250 --> 08:21.876
It's a '39,
and you, too, Mama.

08:21.960 --> 08:23.420
A '39 Chevy.

08:25.672 --> 08:28.383
So, Marie, you have
some news for us?

08:30.176 --> 08:33.972
Yes, sir. Mama, Daddy,

08:36.057 --> 08:39.519
Ernie, I got married again.

08:41.980 --> 08:43.773
To a very nice man.

08:44.941 --> 08:49.612
The main thing
is I can support
you now, baby.

08:56.411 --> 09:00.165
I want you to come back
and live with me in Elmira.

09:04.002 --> 09:07.756
How far away is Elmira?

09:09.090 --> 09:13.428
It's not far at all, baby.
It's just a few hours away.

09:16.264 --> 09:18.183
I think you'll like it.

09:20.518 --> 09:22.812
GRANDMA:
You gonna love it, baby.

09:23.563 --> 09:24.856
(GRANDMA CHUCKLING)

09:28.526 --> 09:29.611
Bye, Will.

09:29.694 --> 09:30.695
Bye, Ernie.

09:33.656 --> 09:36.618
So, I'll see you soon.

09:54.010 --> 09:55.303
(HONKING)

10:44.644 --> 10:45.687
(WHISTLE BLOWING)

10:45.770 --> 10:51.109
Come on, boys. Line up!
Line up! I got some new
jerseys here for you.

10:51.526 --> 10:53.486
Wait till you see these.

10:53.570 --> 10:55.154
(EXCLAIMS)

10:55.238 --> 10:58.700
Here you go,
Mike, Aaron, Nick.

10:59.742 --> 11:01.661
Patrick, there's
one for you.

11:01.744 --> 11:06.165
You been waiting for these,
I know it. Here you go,
Peewee. Put it on.

11:06.583 --> 11:07.709
Uh...

11:10.253 --> 11:12.881
I'm sorry, boys.
That's all there are.

11:13.798 --> 11:17.760
Don't worry. The other
team won't have any
trouble recognizing you.

11:17.844 --> 11:18.845
(CHUCKLES)

11:20.471 --> 11:21.931
Come on! Huddle!

11:22.015 --> 11:23.266
Reggie!

11:26.477 --> 11:27.604
Davis.

11:29.230 --> 11:31.149
Just give him the ball.

11:32.233 --> 11:33.985
REGGIE: Ready?
ALL: Ready!

11:34.777 --> 11:35.862
ALL: Break!

11:37.947 --> 11:39.157
Ready!

11:43.620 --> 11:44.829
Hike!

12:05.892 --> 12:06.935
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

12:07.018 --> 12:08.519
(ALL CHEERING)

12:16.027 --> 12:17.695
That your son?

12:17.779 --> 12:20.156
Yes. Yes, it is.

12:20.239 --> 12:22.742
Al Malette,
Elmira <i>Star-Gazette.</i>

12:23.284 --> 12:24.953
What's his name?

12:25.370 --> 12:28.706
Ernie.
His name is
Ernie Davis.

12:29.040 --> 12:31.751
Ernie Davis.

12:32.251 --> 12:33.419
MAN: Break!

12:45.306 --> 12:47.141
So you're the man
who owns Jim Brown.

12:47.225 --> 12:49.727
I own the team.
He's his own man.
Hey, Jim!

12:49.811 --> 12:51.062
I think you've
done enough of that.

12:51.145 --> 12:52.939
REX: Mr. Modell,
just a few more?

12:53.022 --> 12:54.607
This is the last
time he's gonna
be on this field.

12:54.691 --> 12:57.026
You've got plenty, Rex.
Boys, thank you very much.

12:57.110 --> 13:00.113
That's good, we got it.
Jim, come over here.

13:00.571 --> 13:03.992
All right, fellas.
Take a couple like this.

13:04.075 --> 13:05.118
Nice big smile, Jim.

13:05.201 --> 13:06.494
Hey, Jim, you
think you're ready?

13:06.577 --> 13:07.870
Right here, Jim, look
here. Right here...

13:07.954 --> 13:10.623
So Jim Brown's gonna
be wearing a Cleveland
Browns jersey.

13:10.707 --> 13:11.874
How's it feel?

13:11.958 --> 13:13.001
It feels right.

13:13.084 --> 13:14.293
Jim? Right here, Jim.

13:14.377 --> 13:15.920
Dan Boyle,
<i>Chicago Sun.</i>

13:16.004 --> 13:18.047
You had a terrific year
here at Syracuse, Jim.

13:18.131 --> 13:21.551
Seven yards a carry, broke
records, took your team
to the Cotton Bowl,

13:21.634 --> 13:24.345
number one draft choice,
signed a big contract.

13:24.429 --> 13:28.516
I'm guessing you're pretty
happy with the way
things turned out.

13:28.599 --> 13:31.561
I could be happier.
You left something out.

13:31.769 --> 13:34.188
You talking about
the Heisman Trophy, Jim?

13:34.272 --> 13:37.942
I didn't win that.
Actually, no Negro
has ever won it.

13:38.401 --> 13:40.945
And you're saying
you should have?

13:45.158 --> 13:46.909
Now, if I say that

13:47.326 --> 13:49.704
the papers tomorrow
will tell the story
of the angry Negro

13:49.787 --> 13:51.914
who doesn't
know his place.

13:52.373 --> 13:54.542
I know my place,
gentlemen.

13:54.959 --> 13:57.462
It just may not be
where you like it.

13:57.545 --> 13:59.088
Next question.

14:05.553 --> 14:08.723
Hey, Coach.
Coach, let me
ask you something.

14:08.806 --> 14:11.809
How do you ever expect
to replace Jimmy Brown?

14:20.985 --> 14:24.530
BELL: Glen Boyd, Cedar Rapids
High. Team won state.

14:25.490 --> 14:28.868
He has a C average
but a tested IQ of 120.

14:28.951 --> 14:30.369
That means he's lazy.

14:30.453 --> 14:32.455
Ben, the kid has
a five-yard average.

14:32.538 --> 14:34.707
I don't care.
He's lazy.
I don't want him.

14:34.791 --> 14:36.584
Next!
Wally Purdue,

14:36.667 --> 14:39.295
Bridgeport Academy,
six varsity letters.

14:39.378 --> 14:41.589
He's healing from
an ankle fracture but...

14:41.672 --> 14:43.091
But bullshit!

14:43.591 --> 14:47.136
Anybody else?
Maybe someone who
isn't hurt or lazy?

14:48.346 --> 14:50.598
Isn't there
a kid from Elmira?

14:51.265 --> 14:54.685
Yeah, Ernie Davis.
Elmira Free Academy.

14:55.520 --> 14:58.523
Running back,
1,300 yards
on 179 carries.

14:58.606 --> 15:02.652
Led his team to a state
championship. Why the hell
didn't we look at him first?

15:02.735 --> 15:05.029
Well, he's a
Negro boy, Ben.

15:06.405 --> 15:09.283
Is this a new trend,
or is it just my luck?

15:09.367 --> 15:10.618
It's a new trend.

15:11.911 --> 15:14.705
He might remind you
of somebody we know.

15:15.665 --> 15:18.876
Too old to butt heads
with another Jim Brown.

15:20.086 --> 15:21.379
Roll it.

15:25.591 --> 15:28.094
SIMMONS: There he is
on the left, number 55.

15:30.429 --> 15:32.682
Right now, he's...
Now watch him here.

15:32.765 --> 15:37.103
He breaks through both
tackles and look at that,
into the secondary.

15:37.478 --> 15:39.897
There he goes,
30-yard line,

15:40.189 --> 15:43.442
40-yard line, 50,

15:43.526 --> 15:48.656
40, 30, 20, 10.

15:51.242 --> 15:54.036
Touchdown. Wow!

15:58.082 --> 15:59.625
He have any offers yet?

15:59.709 --> 16:00.877
About 50.

16:02.753 --> 16:04.005
(SIGHS)

16:04.088 --> 16:05.214
Shit.

16:06.591 --> 16:09.343
BROWN: It's all chrome
inside there. Feel that.

16:09.427 --> 16:11.679
No, no, no.
Not that, that's the gas.
Better step on the brake.

16:11.762 --> 16:12.763
Oh!

16:12.847 --> 16:16.392
There you go. You
got tiny legs. She's
gonna love this, right?

16:16.475 --> 16:18.269
Mighty nice
car, Jim.

16:22.190 --> 16:23.816
Do me a favor,
wait upstairs.

16:23.900 --> 16:25.026
Okay then.

16:32.116 --> 16:36.037
What's on your mind,
Coach? I take it this
isn't a social call.

16:36.579 --> 16:41.209
All right, look, there's
this kid, and I want you
to help me recruit him.

16:41.292 --> 16:43.669
You want me to help you?

16:44.128 --> 16:45.963
You're leaving us a
hell of a hole, Jim.

16:46.047 --> 16:50.218
And we are up against
the big boys. We've got
Pitt, UCLA, Texas.

16:50.301 --> 16:52.678
You mean he's colored.

16:52.762 --> 16:54.222
He's a Negro, yes.

16:54.847 --> 16:57.099
You can't talk to Negroes?

16:57.183 --> 16:58.267
I can't...

16:59.477 --> 17:04.232
I'm not good at that salesman
stuff. Not much of a dancer,
you know that.

17:05.650 --> 17:10.154
I know this wasn't the most
welcoming place for you,
but that's not my fault.

17:10.238 --> 17:13.616
I can only control
what happens on 100
yards of gridiron.

17:13.699 --> 17:15.910
But I do know Cleveland never
would have heard of you

17:15.992 --> 17:18.704
if you hadn't come
here to play for me.

17:22.124 --> 17:26.045
What I did here
was on my back
and my sweat.

17:26.878 --> 17:28.422
What good would
your time be here

17:28.506 --> 17:32.093
if you're not willing
to help the next
kid get his chance?

17:33.636 --> 17:35.137
A kid like you.

17:40.268 --> 17:42.103
He's got talent, Jim.

17:43.562 --> 17:45.856
Maybe even your
kind of talent.

17:47.692 --> 17:50.736
Didn't mention
anything in your telegram
about bringing Jim Brown.

17:50.820 --> 17:53.197
I hope you don't
mind signing a couple
hundred autographs.

17:53.281 --> 17:55.783
Ha! Jim loves to sign
autographs, don't you?

17:55.866 --> 17:57.827
You know, Jim,
I'm a Syracuse
man myself.

17:57.910 --> 17:59.203
Class of '31.

17:59.287 --> 18:00.538
You don't say.

18:02.999 --> 18:05.543
Is that Bill Clark
from Notre Dame?

18:05.751 --> 18:07.753
MARTY: Yeah,
been here all week.

18:08.129 --> 18:11.966
Yeah, not enough
he steals Ramsey right
out from under my nose.

18:12.049 --> 18:14.802
That's your man
right there, Ernie Davis.

18:14.885 --> 18:17.847
11 varsity letters.
Plays baseball, too.

18:18.222 --> 18:21.309
In fact, there's not
a sport he doesn't play.

18:21.392 --> 18:22.476
(MARTY BLOWS WHISTLE)

18:22.560 --> 18:24.395
Try it one more time.

18:25.438 --> 18:27.023
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

18:42.663 --> 18:44.582
Let's see what he does.

18:55.426 --> 18:57.511
He's too fast
for these kids.

18:57.595 --> 18:59.096
He's too fast
for anybody.

19:00.890 --> 19:02.433
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

19:14.695 --> 19:18.491
Ben Schwartzwalder.
Head coach, Syracuse
University Orangemen.

19:18.574 --> 19:19.700
Pleasure to
meet you, sir.

19:19.784 --> 19:22.036
Pleasure to
meet you, son.

19:22.745 --> 19:24.789
Do you know
why I'm here?

19:25.164 --> 19:27.416
Same reason as
Notre Dame, sir?

19:27.500 --> 19:29.794
Yeah, same reason.

19:30.336 --> 19:34.423
But don't just take my
word for it. Jim! Jim!

19:35.091 --> 19:36.217
I'll be right back.
Thank you.

19:36.300 --> 19:37.843
There's another fan
who'd like to tell you

19:37.927 --> 19:41.097
how much he'd
like to see you
come play for us.

19:41.180 --> 19:42.390
Jim...
Brown.

19:42.473 --> 19:45.893
2,091 rushing yards,
5.8 yards of carry,

19:45.976 --> 19:49.230
132 yards and
three touchdowns
in the Cotton Bowl.

19:49.980 --> 19:51.732
We lost the Cotton Bowl.

19:51.816 --> 19:54.610
But that sweep
where you cut
back to the middle?

19:54.693 --> 19:57.738
My mama and me watched
that game on a television
set in Sears and Roebuck.

19:57.822 --> 20:00.074
She's a big fan
of yours, too.

20:00.408 --> 20:01.409
Oh!

20:01.492 --> 20:02.743
Is she?

20:05.121 --> 20:07.748
Mr. Brown?
I hope you like
caramel cake.

20:07.832 --> 20:08.958
I do, thank you.

20:09.041 --> 20:10.126
Here you go.

20:12.044 --> 20:15.297
I understand you're
from Pennsylvania,
Mr. Davis.

20:16.257 --> 20:18.008
What brings you up
here to New York?

20:18.092 --> 20:19.760
I asked him to come.

20:19.844 --> 20:21.971
To help me make up my mind.

20:22.471 --> 20:25.641
That's good
to have family
like that.

20:26.183 --> 20:28.102
You close to your family,
Mr. Schwartzwalder?

20:28.185 --> 20:30.813
I have a wife
and two daughters.

20:31.147 --> 20:34.400
And they never ask my
opinion about anything.

20:34.483 --> 20:35.526
(ALL CHUCKLE)

20:35.609 --> 20:37.194
Seems to work.

20:40.072 --> 20:41.282
Mr. Brown?

20:41.365 --> 20:42.366
Yes, sir.

20:42.450 --> 20:45.161
Were you the first
in your family to
go to college?

20:45.244 --> 20:46.912
Yes, sir, I was.

20:48.330 --> 20:53.878
And what's it
like at Syracuse
for men like us?

20:58.382 --> 21:00.676
It's great.
It's good.

21:08.058 --> 21:11.937
I suppose I'd say
it's not that different
than a lot of places.

21:14.440 --> 21:16.901
This cake is delicious.

21:20.946 --> 21:25.910
BROWN: I want you
to go out. Keep going.
Back. Back. All right.

21:26.243 --> 21:29.121
Mr. Brown,
I'm not real
big on lacrosse.

21:29.205 --> 21:30.915
Jim.
Jim.

21:31.373 --> 21:33.667
Okay, let's see
what you've got.

21:33.751 --> 21:35.002
(GRUNTS)

21:35.836 --> 21:38.255
It's not as easy
as it looks, is it?

21:38.339 --> 21:39.340
I'm all right.

21:41.425 --> 21:43.719
You see, lacrosse
isn't just a sport.

21:43.802 --> 21:47.848
The Indians used it to
settle their conflicts
and heal the sick.

21:47.932 --> 21:50.935
They also played it as
a preparation for war.

21:52.686 --> 21:55.856
Make no mistake,
there's a war
in this country,

21:55.940 --> 21:58.984
but for men like us,
it's not on
the football field.

21:59.068 --> 22:02.613
So if all you nice folks
are offering the same thing,

22:02.696 --> 22:04.198
what makes you different?

22:04.281 --> 22:05.282
Well, Syracuse...

22:05.366 --> 22:07.284
Not Syracuse. You.

22:08.118 --> 22:10.037
I'm not sure I follow
you, Mr. Davis.

22:10.120 --> 22:14.291
My grandson might be
spending the next four
years listening to you,

22:15.626 --> 22:17.336
learning from you.

22:18.629 --> 22:21.340
So, I suppose
what I'm asking,
Mr. Schwartzwalder,

22:21.423 --> 22:25.135
is what kind
of man are you?

22:27.972 --> 22:30.558
I just want to be
the best player
I can be, you know.

22:30.641 --> 22:32.476
I want to be
like you, Jim Brown,

22:32.560 --> 22:35.813
first-team Ail-American
then straight to the NFL,

22:35.896 --> 22:39.858
and I need you to tell
me exactly where I
gotta be to get there.

22:40.526 --> 22:45.155
Look, if you go to
Syracuse, it's not
gonna be easy for you.

22:46.156 --> 22:49.493
But Schwartzwalder,
he's one of the best
coaches in college ball.

22:49.577 --> 22:53.372
Now you're fast,
but he'll make you faster.

22:53.956 --> 22:57.459
You run hard,
he'll show you
how to run harder.

22:58.877 --> 23:02.381
And you're good,
but he'll make you better.

23:03.424 --> 23:04.883
And if you ever
tell him I said that,

23:04.967 --> 23:09.388
I'll jump on the first
plane from Cleveland and
come and wring your neck.

23:11.181 --> 23:13.100
Now let's get out of here.

23:13.183 --> 23:17.813
Let me tell you something
about Jim and I, we had
our differences at times.

23:18.897 --> 23:23.360
So whatever he told you
about me, I would take it
with a grain of salt.

23:25.696 --> 23:28.324
Even if he said you
were a good coach?

23:29.199 --> 23:30.659
(SCOFFS)

23:30.743 --> 23:35.581
Well, in that case, son,
I would tell you that too
much salt is bad for you.

24:02.566 --> 24:05.402
Ernie? Ernie Davis?

24:05.736 --> 24:07.363
How'd you guess?

24:07.446 --> 24:08.530
Welcome.

24:08.614 --> 24:11.408
I'm Lew Andreas,
the athletic
director. Come on!

24:11.492 --> 24:13.786
I'll give you
a tour of the campus
on the way to your dorm.

24:13.869 --> 24:15.537
All right.
Syracuse has a storied

24:15.621 --> 24:17.623
academic tradition, Ernie.
Really?

24:17.706 --> 24:20.125
Steven Crane attended
the university in 1891

24:20.209 --> 24:22.836
and wrote <i>The Red
Badge of Courage...</i>
Hey, Lew!

24:22.920 --> 24:26.507
Harry! Sorry, I'll be
right back. Right back.

24:27.007 --> 24:28.884
Harry.
How are you?

26:14.990 --> 26:19.036
No one from here has
ever won, if that's
what you're looking for.

26:20.746 --> 26:23.207
No harm in dreaming,
right, Coach?

26:23.415 --> 26:27.294
It's not about
winning trophies, Davis.
It's about winning games.

26:27.377 --> 26:29.379
I'll see you at practice.

26:32.216 --> 26:33.967
Get up! Get up!

26:34.051 --> 26:36.845
That was plum awful!
Now, last one runs a lap.

26:36.929 --> 26:38.388
Let's go!

26:39.598 --> 26:40.808
Run a lap.

26:40.891 --> 26:42.059
ALL: ...five, six...

26:42.643 --> 26:45.395
Youmans, you move
like a walrus.

26:45.938 --> 26:48.315
Come on! Like a big,
old elephant walrus!

26:48.398 --> 26:51.318
Gerhard, goose-step.
Make your ancestors proud.

26:51.401 --> 26:52.903
Ease up, Davis.

26:53.403 --> 26:55.405
What are you smiling at?

26:55.489 --> 26:57.991
This fine institution
is giving you three
hots and a cot.

26:58.075 --> 27:00.327
I do not intend to let
them waste their money.

27:00.410 --> 27:01.870
Get them up, come on.

27:01.954 --> 27:03.080
Right about now,
I bet you're wondering

27:03.163 --> 27:04.998
what happened to
that nice gentleman
that visited your house

27:05.082 --> 27:07.084
and begged you
to come here, huh?

27:07.167 --> 27:09.837
Let's go! Now make
no mistake, gentlemen.

27:09.920 --> 27:14.591
No matter what anyone else
tells you, you are not here
to just play football.

27:14.675 --> 27:16.510
You are offside.

27:16.593 --> 27:19.012
BEN: You are here
at Syracuse
to win games.

27:19.096 --> 27:23.183
And you can't win
games if you can't
out-perform the other team.

27:23.267 --> 27:24.977
Don't you step on
my All-Americans.

27:25.060 --> 27:27.563
If you step on my
Ail-Americans, I will
reach down your throat,

27:27.646 --> 27:30.315
grab your donuts
and tie them to
your tonsils!

27:30.399 --> 27:31.525
Good hit!

27:31.608 --> 27:32.568
Take him down!

27:32.651 --> 27:34.903
So, you're the
next Jim Brown, huh?

27:35.237 --> 27:36.530
Yeah, I can see
the resemblance.

27:36.613 --> 27:39.283
Yeah, except Brown
was always mad
about something.

27:39.366 --> 27:41.618
(CHUCKLES) Don't be fooled
by the smile.

27:41.702 --> 27:43.036
Well, he's funnier
than Jimmy.

27:43.120 --> 27:44.121
Yeah.

27:44.204 --> 27:47.249
Well, maybe he
can entertain us.
You dance, Davis?

27:47.332 --> 27:49.084
Not as good
as me, Lundy.

27:49.167 --> 27:51.879
Come on! Get up!
Move! Move! Move! Move!

27:51.962 --> 27:54.214
SCHWEDES: You should
know, you never call
Coach, "Sarge."

27:54.298 --> 27:57.593
He was a captain,
jumped out of airplanes,
stormed a bridge in Normandy.

27:57.676 --> 27:59.803
Killed people,
won medals.

27:59.887 --> 28:02.264
By the way, I'm Gerhard
Schwedes, halfback.

28:02.347 --> 28:05.225
Roger, everybody calls
me Hound Dog though.

28:05.309 --> 28:07.269
Maury Youmans, center.

28:07.352 --> 28:10.314
I'll be keeping your
jersey clean next year.

28:10.939 --> 28:13.650
He embarrassed you!
Embarrassed you!

28:14.234 --> 28:17.112
BEN: I want you to move Davis
from freshman to varsity.

28:17.195 --> 28:19.907
But he won't be eligible
to play in any games, Ben.

28:19.990 --> 28:22.159
Why don't we just let
him catch his stride
with the other freshmen?

28:22.242 --> 28:24.661
First, when he does
become eligible next year,

28:24.745 --> 28:26.496
I want him to hit
the ground running.

28:26.580 --> 28:29.499
Second, he's gonna
raise everybody's game.

28:29.583 --> 28:31.835
He'll probably be
the best running back
they face all year.

28:31.919 --> 28:32.920
I got you.

28:33.003 --> 28:35.422
Third, that's just
the way I want it done.

28:35.505 --> 28:37.215
(BLOWING WHISTLE)

28:37.674 --> 28:40.928
Jack Buckley, right tackle,
sophomore. Call me JB.

28:41.845 --> 28:44.598
I was a defensive end
in high school. Philly.

28:44.681 --> 28:47.309
But I think they're
gonna move me to tackle.

28:47.392 --> 28:49.603
What we up to?
Three miles?

28:49.686 --> 28:51.271
Don't know.
Never count.

28:51.355 --> 28:52.814
You hear a train?

28:52.898 --> 28:54.274
Why?
Is it making
you nervous?

28:54.358 --> 28:56.652
No, I'm not nervous.

28:57.235 --> 28:58.779
Can we get off
these tracks?

28:58.862 --> 29:00.948
Yeah, I'm sorry.
I'm just used to it.

29:01.031 --> 29:02.950
And when you use
your meal voucher
in the student union...

29:03.075 --> 29:04.952
Right.
...stay away from
the meatloaf.

29:05.035 --> 29:06.662
What else?
Girls.

29:06.745 --> 29:10.499
You'll find a Negro polar bear
before you find a Negro coed.

29:11.625 --> 29:14.711
Good morning, sir.
Beautiful day, isn't it?

29:16.463 --> 29:20.175
I swear, sometimes you feel
like you're on the moon here.

29:22.344 --> 29:24.554
SARETTE: Yes, yes,
that's her sister.

29:25.597 --> 29:27.474
Sarette, what did Petey
say about that broad?

29:27.557 --> 29:29.685
Yeah, it's her
little sister.

29:29.768 --> 29:33.480
I don't know about our
team yet, but theirs is
in mid-season form.

29:33.563 --> 29:35.524
At least her sister is.

29:44.241 --> 29:45.826
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

29:53.000 --> 29:54.459
ERNIE: Coach
wanted to see me?

29:54.543 --> 29:55.961
He's in his office.

29:58.130 --> 29:59.339
Knock.

30:00.590 --> 30:02.259
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

30:11.184 --> 30:13.353
You wanted to
see me, Coach?

30:13.979 --> 30:15.272
Mmm-hmm.

30:15.772 --> 30:17.941
Davis, my system
is simple.

30:18.400 --> 30:20.110
Conditioning,
teamwork.

30:20.193 --> 30:23.196
And on my team, I expect every
player to know his job.

30:23.280 --> 30:25.032
Know his place on the field.

30:25.115 --> 30:27.951
Quarterback,
running back,
lineman.

30:28.326 --> 30:31.663
That way, nobody
steps on anybody's toes.

30:32.789 --> 30:35.042
Same holds true
off the field.

30:35.667 --> 30:37.377
I'm not sure how
you mean, Coach.

30:37.461 --> 30:38.462
Well...

30:39.963 --> 30:43.383
There are some lines
that some people don't
care to see crossed,

30:43.467 --> 30:46.303
just like there are some toes
that shouldn't be stepped on.

30:46.386 --> 30:50.057
And I expect my players
not to cross those lines.

30:53.810 --> 30:58.356
Now, you must
have a girlfriend
back home, right?

30:58.440 --> 31:00.650
Good-looking
fellow like you.

31:00.984 --> 31:03.862
You might want to
keep in touch with her.

31:07.157 --> 31:11.453
You're a smart kid, Davis.
I don't have to spell
it out for you, do I?

31:13.413 --> 31:15.207
Anything else, Coach?

31:16.875 --> 31:17.918
No.

31:18.001 --> 31:19.002
May I go now?

31:21.880 --> 31:23.006
Yes.

31:30.055 --> 31:32.265
JACK: We call that,
"The white girl speech,"

31:32.349 --> 31:33.892
and don't worry,
we all get it.

31:33.975 --> 31:36.937
That's funny.
I don't remember seeing that
in the campus brochure, JB.

31:37.020 --> 31:38.063
(CHUCKLES)

31:38.146 --> 31:39.481
Avatus Stone.

31:39.564 --> 31:40.565
Avatus what?

31:40.857 --> 31:43.276
Avatus Stone.
Quarterback. Negro.

31:43.360 --> 31:45.487
First one Schwartzwalder
recruited here.

31:45.570 --> 31:46.780
What happened to him?

31:46.863 --> 31:47.989
He got run off.

31:48.073 --> 31:49.449
What do you mean,
"Run off?"

31:49.533 --> 31:51.952
One night, just
disappeared. Gone.

31:52.035 --> 31:53.745
And then Jimmy
Brown shows up,

31:53.829 --> 31:55.914
and all Jim
hears is, "Don't be
like Avatus Stone.

31:55.997 --> 31:57.582
"Whatever you
do, don't be like
Avatus Stone."

31:57.666 --> 32:00.210
Wait. But what did he do?
Did he kill somebody?

32:00.293 --> 32:02.921
Worse. He dated
a white girl.

32:03.797 --> 32:05.507
Majorette, blonde.

32:05.715 --> 32:09.803
Schwartzwalder wouldn't
even give Jim a scholarship
until sophomore year.

32:09.886 --> 32:11.138
Made him prove himself.

32:11.221 --> 32:12.347
Yeah.

32:12.430 --> 32:16.685
Just goes to show, Coach
likes winning more than
he dislikes Negroes.

32:16.893 --> 32:17.978
A little.

32:18.061 --> 32:19.271
See you
at the room.

32:41.209 --> 32:42.252
Hey.

32:49.968 --> 32:51.761
Excuse me,
Hound Dog.

33:06.651 --> 33:08.486
LUNDY: Would you look
at that, boys?

33:08.570 --> 33:12.866
If it isn't enough they
let a freshman dress
in the varsity locker,

33:12.949 --> 33:15.035
now they went and anointed
him the second coming of
Jim Brown.

33:15.118 --> 33:16.119
(ALL LAUGHING)

33:16.203 --> 33:17.704
What's your
problem, Lundy?

33:17.787 --> 33:20.624
My problem is I was raised
to believe you should have
to earn things.

33:20.707 --> 33:22.626
That's not all you
were raised to believe,
now was it?

33:22.709 --> 33:24.169
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

33:24.961 --> 33:26.213
You got a big mouth, JB.

33:26.296 --> 33:27.547
Yeah, I do.

33:30.675 --> 33:32.219
SIMMONS: How about
the next play, Ben?

33:32.302 --> 33:35.347
This'll be strong load
right, 42 shovel pass.

33:36.514 --> 33:38.725
We can use
this third short.

33:39.935 --> 33:42.062
Strong load right.
Right, 42 shovel pass.

33:42.145 --> 33:43.939
What you got there, Davis?

33:46.441 --> 33:48.485
It's this jersey, Coach.

33:48.568 --> 33:50.820
What, something
wrong with it?

33:50.904 --> 33:51.905
Yeah, I...

33:51.988 --> 33:54.074
What is it?
Too big?
Too tight, what?

33:54.157 --> 33:55.200
Oh, no.
Not at all.
It's just...

33:55.283 --> 33:57.452
Then what is it?

33:57.827 --> 33:59.788
Somebody made
a mistake.

34:00.455 --> 34:02.707
They gave me
the wrong number.

34:03.625 --> 34:06.670
Mr. Davis, I put that
jersey in your locker.

34:06.753 --> 34:08.545
Are you accusing me
of making a mistake?

34:08.630 --> 34:10.632
No, sir.
Well then, what?

34:13.677 --> 34:15.178
Coach, I'm...

34:17.597 --> 34:19.266
I'm not Jim Brown.

34:20.934 --> 34:22.518
God, I hope not!

34:24.562 --> 34:26.523
And, God, I hope so.

34:27.148 --> 34:29.025
That is your number.

34:29.484 --> 34:33.655
The day you're not up to it,
I'll take it away as quick
as a hiccup.

34:34.364 --> 34:36.199
Now, get out of here.

34:40.786 --> 34:43.123
Tight right, 34 right dig.
On one. On one. Ready.

34:43.206 --> 34:44.291
ALL: Break!

34:44.958 --> 34:47.710
Offense, I want to see
you fire off the ball.

34:47.793 --> 34:49.629
Fire off the ball.

34:49.713 --> 34:50.714
Red?
Sir!

34:50.797 --> 34:52.799
Are you in
or out there?

34:54.467 --> 34:56.553
Strong left,
strong left!

34:57.053 --> 34:58.805
Strong left.
Why don't you watch
the sweep, right there?

34:58.888 --> 35:00.307
PLAYER: Sir!
Ready?

35:01.224 --> 35:02.392
SARETTE: On one.

35:11.818 --> 35:13.236
God damn it!

35:14.738 --> 35:16.281
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

35:17.407 --> 35:20.035
Lundy, you got
yourself planted.

35:20.118 --> 35:23.913
Get off your heels
and get after it.
That was embarrassing.

35:26.458 --> 35:27.459
Davis looks good.

35:27.542 --> 35:29.044
Looks good, Ben.

35:31.338 --> 35:32.630
Five, three,
cover two. Ready?

35:32.714 --> 35:33.923
ALL: Break!

35:35.091 --> 35:39.179
Double tight, double
tight. Watch the sweep
left! Watch the sweep!

35:54.527 --> 35:56.112
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

35:57.864 --> 35:59.491
(WHISTLE BLOWING)

35:59.574 --> 36:01.034
(ALL EXCLAIM)

36:01.618 --> 36:03.328
That was a cheap shot.

36:03.411 --> 36:06.873
Oh, he's gonna get
a lot worse than that
before he's done here.

36:06.956 --> 36:09.292
You've got
something
to say, 44?

36:15.465 --> 36:17.050
You all right?
Yeah.

36:18.218 --> 36:20.804
You can't let him
treat you like that
and not say nothing.

36:20.887 --> 36:23.973
That's all right.
I do my talking
on the field.

36:58.508 --> 37:00.009
(ALL EXCLAIM)

37:00.885 --> 37:02.470
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

37:14.691 --> 37:16.234
Hey, hey! Come on!

37:16.317 --> 37:17.777
Hey, come on!

37:19.362 --> 37:22.824
All right,
all right, all right,
all right, all right.

37:27.203 --> 37:28.788
Don't ever make me
look bad again.

37:28.872 --> 37:30.957
Back to the huddle, Lundy.

37:31.040 --> 37:34.752
You got away with a lot back
in high school 'cause you were
bigger than everybody else.

37:34.836 --> 37:36.671
Those days are done.

37:36.754 --> 37:38.840
You got it?
Got it, Coach.

37:40.383 --> 37:41.759
Good block.

37:42.719 --> 37:44.220
Now listen up.

37:44.888 --> 37:48.224
If you practice half-assed,
you will play half-assed.

37:48.725 --> 37:50.685
Now, we have Boston
College in two weeks

37:50.768 --> 37:54.397
and I would like
not to get blown out
in our own stadium.

37:56.733 --> 37:58.401
Now play football.

37:59.235 --> 38:00.904
Let's go. Good work.

38:01.321 --> 38:03.490
(BAND PLAYING
ROCK 'N' ROLL MUSIC)

38:03.573 --> 38:05.241
<i>(SINGING)</i>

38:19.088 --> 38:21.341
Surprise, surprise.
Will you look at this?

38:21.424 --> 38:23.676
They're saying
Pete Dawkins is gonna
take home the Heisman.

38:23.760 --> 38:27.847
Well, he rushed for over
1,000 yards, and has almost
as many receiving yards, JB.

38:27.931 --> 38:29.265
He's gotta
be real good.

38:29.349 --> 38:32.018
Yeah, well, he's
definitely real white.

38:34.562 --> 38:36.940
This thing's
like a love letter.

38:40.527 --> 38:41.528
JB, look.

38:41.611 --> 38:42.612
What?

38:44.739 --> 38:45.740
Hey!

38:46.074 --> 38:47.742
Negro polar bears.

38:48.952 --> 38:51.246
Who knew they
traveled in pairs?

38:51.412 --> 38:52.622
(CHATTERING)

38:53.623 --> 38:55.250
Ready?
For what?

38:55.333 --> 38:58.336
You're not ready.
Come on, let's go.
Which one do you like?

38:58.419 --> 38:59.712
Which one do you like?

38:59.796 --> 39:01.172
The one on the right.

39:01.256 --> 39:02.382
Good evening, ladies.

39:02.465 --> 39:03.466
Good evening.

39:03.550 --> 39:05.218
I'd like a Pepsi.
The same.

39:05.301 --> 39:07.053
And could you bring us
some of those deviled eggs?

39:07.136 --> 39:09.889
You don't even be
eating no deviled egg.

39:09.973 --> 39:11.307
(LAUGHING)

39:11.641 --> 39:13.560
I'm so sorry.
You go to Syracuse?

39:13.643 --> 39:15.270
I didn't know.

39:15.812 --> 39:17.564
Yes, we go to Syracuse,
but if you'd like,

39:17.647 --> 39:20.858
we can jump in the kitchen,
whip you up some grits
and gravy, ma'am.

39:20.942 --> 39:22.318
Get them, Ernie.

39:22.402 --> 39:24.571
I'm Gloria.
This is my friend...

39:24.654 --> 39:25.697
Sarah.

39:25.780 --> 39:27.574
She's visiting
from Cornell.

39:27.657 --> 39:31.786
Gloria and Sarah.
Okay. I'm Jack Buckley,
but you call me JB.

39:31.869 --> 39:33.121
JB.
JB.

39:33.204 --> 39:35.206
And this is my
friend, Ernie.

39:35.290 --> 39:36.916
How do you do?

39:37.000 --> 39:38.001
Very well.

39:39.836 --> 39:42.463
So, what are you
guys studying?

39:43.256 --> 39:45.717
Well, a little bit
of everything.

39:45.800 --> 39:47.677
Math, basic literature...

39:47.760 --> 39:49.095
We're on the
football team.

39:49.178 --> 39:50.471
And that.

39:51.556 --> 39:52.640
GLORIA: Oh!

39:53.933 --> 39:55.852
I don't really know
too much about football.

39:55.935 --> 39:57.812
Neither does he.

39:57.895 --> 39:59.355
(ALL LAUGHING)

39:59.731 --> 40:03.026
All kidding aside,
Gloria, would you
care to dance?

40:04.736 --> 40:06.112
All right.

40:17.707 --> 40:18.958
(SIGHS)

40:24.505 --> 40:26.966
So, Sarah, what
are you studying?

40:27.050 --> 40:30.595
I'm majoring in education,
with a minor in
social sciences.

40:30.887 --> 40:31.929
Oh!

40:32.013 --> 40:34.349
And you?
What are you studying?

40:34.849 --> 40:37.435
Just some basic
courses right now,
some math,

40:38.394 --> 40:40.021
some English.

40:41.022 --> 40:42.982
Look, I know what
you're thinking.

40:43.066 --> 40:45.777
That since I'm not here
because of my grades,

40:45.860 --> 40:47.403
or my money,

40:47.487 --> 40:49.739
that I'm not
a serious person.

40:50.448 --> 40:52.158
You're wrong.

40:52.241 --> 40:53.868
So, you know what
I'm thinking, do you?

40:55.787 --> 40:57.497
Fine, Mr. Serious.

40:58.665 --> 41:00.875
What am I thinking
right now?

41:45.712 --> 41:49.549
<i>ANNOUNCER: Rain still
coming down steadily
here at Archbold Stadium.</i>

41:49.632 --> 41:52.051
<i>The last chance
for the Orangemen.</i>

41:59.767 --> 42:02.979
<i>The Orangemen can really use
a little help out there.</i>

42:03.646 --> 42:07.316
<i>Let's hope their
recruiting is better
than their running game.</i>

42:07.400 --> 42:08.484
QUARTERBACK: Hike!

42:13.030 --> 42:16.826
<i>And for the Syracuse faithful,
there's a sense of disbelief,</i>

42:16.909 --> 42:20.037
<i>as Holy Cross has knocked
off the mighty Orangemen.</i>

42:20.538 --> 42:21.914
BELL: Let's go, ladies.
Pick it up!

42:21.998 --> 42:23.374
BEN: Let's go.
Knees up.
Knees up.

42:23.458 --> 42:24.500
Pain is how you learn.

42:24.584 --> 42:25.585
Come on!

42:25.668 --> 42:29.547
Gentlemen, it is not okay
to lose to an inferior team,

42:29.630 --> 42:31.966
especially on our home turf!

42:32.300 --> 42:36.262
Now, we gave no effort out
on that field tonight, so
we should feel it now!

42:36.345 --> 42:38.681
Don't you puke
on my gym floor!

42:40.016 --> 42:42.143
Varsity practice only, Ernie.
You don't have to be here.

42:42.226 --> 42:43.352
I know.

42:44.270 --> 42:45.980
I just heard you called
a midnight practice, Coach.

42:46.063 --> 42:47.815
I'm sorry I'm late.

42:48.441 --> 42:50.109
Well, go ahead.
Get in there.

42:50.193 --> 42:51.319
Yes, sir.

42:57.617 --> 43:02.663
BEN: Gentlemen,
do you think you played
good football last year?

43:02.747 --> 43:04.165
Think again.

43:05.208 --> 43:08.294
<i>You think you're here just
to wear a varsity jacket</i>

43:08.377 --> 43:10.296
<i>and impress the ladies?</i>

43:11.339 --> 43:12.757
Think again.

43:13.883 --> 43:17.804
<i>If you think you
know what pain is,
think again.</i>

43:29.065 --> 43:31.526
This is what pain is for.

43:33.027 --> 43:35.655
Now, does anyone
know the last year

43:35.738 --> 43:38.533
that Syracuse won a
national championship?

43:39.742 --> 43:40.827
Hmm?

43:41.577 --> 43:44.872
You're right.
We've never won one.

43:45.581 --> 43:48.751
You are here to
change all that.

43:49.001 --> 43:51.546
<i>ANNOUNCER 1: Ladies
and gentlemen, please
welcome to the field</i>

43:51.629 --> 43:54.549
<i>your Syracuse
University Orangemen.</i>

43:55.007 --> 43:58.427
<i>ANNOUNCER 2: Welcome
to Archbold Stadium,
Syracuse, New York,</i>

43:58.511 --> 44:01.973
<i>where the Orangemen
begin the 1959 campaign.</i>

44:02.431 --> 44:06.936
The expectations for
Ben Schwartzwalder and
the Orangemen are enormous.

44:07.019 --> 44:10.231
This is a football team
that could go unbeaten.

44:34.589 --> 44:36.966
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

45:05.494 --> 45:07.079
(WHISTLE BLOWING)

45:07.163 --> 45:08.372
Hut one!

45:10.291 --> 45:13.294
On first down,
Ernie Davis gets
his first carry

45:13.377 --> 45:15.588
<i>as a member of
the Orangemen.</i>

45:16.505 --> 45:18.090
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

45:18.382 --> 45:20.343
Welcome to
Syracuse football.

45:20.509 --> 45:21.552
(POPS CHUCKLES)

45:21.636 --> 45:24.764
Will... Will, he said
his name on the radio.

45:25.014 --> 45:27.099
Sure did.
I heard it.
I heard it, Pops.

45:27.183 --> 45:32.146
<i>ANNOUNCER: Ernie Davis
certainly has some big shoes
to fill here today.</i>

45:32.229 --> 45:34.941
<i>And after an unsuccessful
series of downs
by the Orangemen,</i>

45:35.024 --> 45:38.110
<i>Kansas takes over on
its own 28-yard line.</i>

45:38.194 --> 45:39.278
QUARTERBACK: Hut!

45:39.695 --> 45:42.740
Let's get after it!
Come on, let's get after it!

45:49.622 --> 45:54.126
The receiver is leveled
by veteran linebacker
Bobby Lundy.

45:54.210 --> 45:56.253
I'm doing your job, 44.

45:56.337 --> 45:57.630
Huddle up!

45:58.381 --> 46:00.800
<i>Ball at the Syracuse
10-yard line.</i>

46:00.883 --> 46:04.095
<i>First down and goal
to go for Kansas.</i>

46:06.555 --> 46:07.974
Yes.
Did he get in?

46:08.057 --> 46:09.976
<i>Did he cross the goal line?</i>

46:10.059 --> 46:12.061
Here's the official signal.

46:13.229 --> 46:14.605
(BLOWING WHISTLE)

46:14.689 --> 46:15.856
Touchdown, Kansas.

46:15.940 --> 46:17.483
BEN: What kind of
pig slop is that?

46:17.566 --> 46:19.652
We haven't gotten
a call all day!

46:19.735 --> 46:22.363
<i>J ay hawks jump
out to a 7-0 lead</i>

46:22.446 --> 46:25.825
<i>here at the very,</i>
<i>very quiet Archbold Stadium.</i>

46:26.033 --> 46:29.996
Here in the second quarter,
Kansas on top of Syracuse,
7-0.

46:30.079 --> 46:31.080
SARETTE: Six regular!
Six regular!

46:31.163 --> 46:34.291
<i>The Orange faithful
still waiting for
something to cheer about.</i>

46:34.375 --> 46:35.459
Hut one!

46:37.420 --> 46:39.130
<i>Sarette back to pass.</i>

46:41.424 --> 46:43.134
<i>Throwing down fie Id.</i>

46:44.051 --> 46:45.845
<i>It's complete
to his tight end</i>

46:45.928 --> 46:48.014
<i>down near the
Kansas 30-yard line.</i>

46:48.097 --> 46:49.724
Way to pick up
the blitz, Ernie!

46:49.807 --> 46:53.185
A superb block on the play,
turned in by Ernie Davis.

46:53.602 --> 46:56.397
<i>Second down,
eight yards to go
for the Orangemen.</i>

46:56.480 --> 46:57.606
SARETTE: Hut!

46:57.940 --> 47:00.484
<i>Toss play once
again to Ernie Davis.</i>

47:03.320 --> 47:05.031
BEN: Get him out there!

47:06.032 --> 47:08.117
Daw's <i>to the
Kansas secondary.</i>

47:09.160 --> 47:10.703
Go, Davis, go!

47:13.205 --> 47:15.291
<i>Look at that young man go!</i>

47:17.084 --> 47:21.338
<i>The Elmira Express
virtually walks into
the end zone!</i>

47:22.173 --> 47:26.260
<i>The Syracuse Orangemen,
now on top of Kansas, 14-7.</i>

47:26.343 --> 47:27.678
Go for one.

47:27.762 --> 47:32.224
<i>And what an impression Ernie
Davis has made on this
crowd here at Archbold.</i>

47:32.725 --> 47:36.771
<i>The Orangemen
just may have found
their next great halfback.</i>

47:47.740 --> 47:48.783
Hey, Ernie.

47:48.866 --> 47:50.701
Hey, fellas,
how you doing?

47:51.327 --> 47:53.329
You guys
coming or going?

47:53.662 --> 47:55.581
Hey. Welcome home, Ernie.

47:55.664 --> 47:56.707
Pops!

47:56.791 --> 47:58.042
They give you
some time off?

47:58.125 --> 48:00.044
Yeah, yeah,
long weekend.

48:00.127 --> 48:02.254
Look at you,
all college boy.

48:02.338 --> 48:03.923
You're just gonna dirty
up my college jacket.

48:04.006 --> 48:05.925
Come on, come on,
let's go inside.
You're too good to hug me?

48:06.008 --> 48:06.967
Look at this!

48:07.051 --> 48:08.094
Let me carry that.
Give me your bag.

48:08.177 --> 48:10.471
If they'd run
you more last week
against Navy,

48:10.554 --> 48:12.431
you would have blown
them jokers off the field.

48:12.515 --> 48:13.808
Will, we won.

48:13.891 --> 48:15.976
Seems like that
coach of yours
like to pass the ball.

48:16.060 --> 48:17.561
I'll get my carries.

48:17.645 --> 48:19.939
Yeah? He promise you that?

48:20.689 --> 48:22.441
No. Thank you, ma'am.
But eventually...
No?

48:22.525 --> 48:24.026
How are your
grades, Ernie?

48:26.028 --> 48:27.530
Ernie?

48:27.613 --> 48:29.949
They're good, Pops, thanks.
I'm keeping them up.

48:30.032 --> 48:32.451
I like history,
and I'm taking
a business course.

48:32.535 --> 48:33.619
That's good.

48:33.702 --> 48:36.789
'Cause football
is just a game.

48:36.872 --> 48:39.583
It's that degree
that's going to
count for something.

48:39.667 --> 48:41.794
Gonna get you a good job.

48:41.877 --> 48:44.255
Where you gonna
get a good job at,
a Negro with a diploma?

48:44.338 --> 48:46.757
AT&T? GM?

48:47.258 --> 48:49.969
It's football
that's gonna
take him someplace.

48:50.052 --> 48:52.388
Otherwise,
he gonna be working
right here with us,

48:52.471 --> 48:53.764
cutting coal,
and you know it.

48:53.848 --> 48:55.057
I wanna apologize for him.

48:55.141 --> 48:56.725
You ain't got to
apologize for me, Pops!

48:56.809 --> 48:58.310
Don't you start
it tonight, Will.

48:58.394 --> 49:00.020
Pops... Guys!
Don't start
it tonight.

49:00.104 --> 49:01.397
Whoa! Whoa! Whoa!

49:01.897 --> 49:03.190
Relax.

49:03.649 --> 49:05.151
You're both right.

49:05.985 --> 49:09.071
Now, my plan A is the
Cleveland Browns. Now,
if that doesn't work out,

49:09.155 --> 49:11.407
plan B is the
New York Giants.

49:13.492 --> 49:16.203
Come on, Ernie.
We don't wanna be late.

49:17.079 --> 49:20.374
Sorry, my dear,
we got things to do,
people to meet.

49:23.294 --> 49:25.171
I'll meet you
outside, Ernie.

49:28.424 --> 49:32.511
MAN: Jim Crow
is alive and well right
here in Pennsylvania.

49:32.595 --> 49:33.637
MAN: Yes, it is.

49:33.721 --> 49:36.056
But we can no
longer willfully
close our eyes

49:36.140 --> 49:40.519
and pretend that we
cannot see that he sees
us as beneath him.

49:40.603 --> 49:42.521
WOMAN: Yes!
No, we cannot.

49:42.605 --> 49:47.193
And we can no longer
stay silent when he tells
us that we cannot speak.

49:47.276 --> 49:48.694
Yes!
That's right!

49:48.777 --> 49:51.739
Abraham Lincoln
stood in a field
at Gettysburg,

49:51.822 --> 49:53.782
and spoke of a new nation.
MAN: That's right.

49:53.866 --> 49:58.746
Uniontown is 100 miles away
from his Gettysburg.

50:00.039 --> 50:02.208
We are still
yet to be equal.

50:02.291 --> 50:08.797
That is why the NAACP is
calling for a nationwide
boycott of Woolworths.

50:09.298 --> 50:10.299
That's right!
That's right!

50:10.382 --> 50:12.009
All right.

50:12.760 --> 50:14.011
Come on.

50:15.679 --> 50:21.393
ALL: Boycott! Boycott!
Boycott! Boycott!
Boycott! Boycott!

50:21.477 --> 50:23.145
WILL: Come to Washington
with us.

50:23.229 --> 50:25.356
There's a bus going
down from the church.

50:25.439 --> 50:27.191
We gonna organize
with Martin Luther King

50:27.274 --> 50:30.402
and let the people
know this country
has got to change.

50:30.486 --> 50:32.738
I don't think I can be
a part of what you want
me to be a part of

50:32.821 --> 50:34.907
right now, Will.
All this.

50:34.990 --> 50:36.450
What you saying?

50:36.533 --> 50:37.868
I got a scholarship.

50:37.952 --> 50:41.705
I can't risk losing
it, and I don't wanna
invite trouble.

50:41.789 --> 50:44.750
I see. Did Emmett Till
invite trouble?
Did Rosa Parks?

50:44.833 --> 50:46.085
Who told you this,
your coach?

50:46.168 --> 50:47.378
You don't understand.

50:47.461 --> 50:49.088
It's a different
world up there.

50:49.171 --> 50:50.256
Is it?

50:50.506 --> 50:52.341
You know,
your coach sound
a lot like Pops.

50:52.424 --> 50:55.803
No understanding
whatsoever with the
troubles in this country.

50:55.886 --> 50:58.430
"You boys got no business
north of Union Street,
you hear me?"

50:58.514 --> 50:59.640
Now, leave Pops
out of this, Will.

50:59.723 --> 51:02.059
Now you got a white
man telling you what
you can and can't do.

51:02.142 --> 51:03.310
Wait a minute. Hold on.
Watch how you talk to me.

51:03.394 --> 51:04.645
That man don't care
nothing about you, Ernie.

51:04.728 --> 51:05.729
You're not there.
You don't know him.

51:07.189 --> 51:09.149
You don't know what
you're talking about.
Tom can toe the line

51:09.233 --> 51:13.237
and carry the ball,
but that man will turn
on you. Just you wait.

51:14.863 --> 51:18.784
You don't think I'm
reminded every minute
of who I am at school?

51:18.867 --> 51:22.997
Everybody there is
watching me, and waiting
for me to make a mistake.

51:23.872 --> 51:25.499
You Ernie Davis.

51:26.250 --> 51:28.669
You got your
name in the paper.

51:28.752 --> 51:32.006
Now that's something for
colored folk around here to
open up a newspaper, Ernie,

51:32.089 --> 51:35.050
and see your name,
your face.

51:36.719 --> 51:40.514
And say, "I know him.
I went to school with him."

51:41.181 --> 51:43.475
They gonna be
looking up to you.

51:43.559 --> 51:47.104
I think you owe them more
than just running a ball.

52:01.702 --> 52:04.121
SIMMONS: The play action
pass was there all day.

52:04.204 --> 52:05.956
It won't be
there the next time.

52:06.040 --> 52:07.207
Why not?

52:07.291 --> 52:11.295
'Cause Boston College
is watching the same
damn game that we are.

52:38.280 --> 52:42.534
All right, we start out
double tight. Tight in
here, tight in there.

52:42.618 --> 52:43.869
Just a normal
double tight.

52:43.952 --> 52:46.205
Just like from
the beginning
of time, Simmy.

52:46.288 --> 52:49.541
Now,
we're gonna take Schwedes
out of the wing position,

52:49.625 --> 52:52.336
and we're gonna
move him into a
three-back formation.

52:52.419 --> 52:54.713
Only shift it over like this.

52:54.797 --> 52:57.841
All right, defense.
What do you do
when you see this?

52:57.925 --> 52:59.760
Now the defense,
they have to shift.

52:59.843 --> 53:00.886
We move to the right.

53:00.969 --> 53:04.431
That's right. Even if
it's shading from nose
up to opposite shoulder.

53:04.515 --> 53:07.518
Our right tackle?
He goes on the left side.

53:08.310 --> 53:09.853
I'm gonna leave the huddle,

53:09.937 --> 53:13.190
and you're gonna
start out right,
just like normal.

53:16.026 --> 53:17.069
Go left, go left!

53:17.152 --> 53:19.196
<i>Except before we're set,
you're gonna run left.</i>

53:19.279 --> 53:20.280
He runs left,

53:20.364 --> 53:22.324
and you're gonna line
up on the left side.

53:22.408 --> 53:23.826
And he sets up
on the left side.

53:26.328 --> 53:29.081
And it's evident
that Boston College
is confused

53:29.164 --> 53:31.250
by the offense
Syracuse is running.

53:31.333 --> 53:33.585
You lost me, Ben.
The right tackle
moves to the left,

53:33.669 --> 53:34.878
he covers the tight end.

53:34.962 --> 53:37.589
But if he's on the left
side, we cover the tight
end, I can't pass to him.

53:37.673 --> 53:41.510
The Holy Cross defenders
are desperately trying to
position themselves

53:41.593 --> 53:43.387
<i>to best play against
this formation.</i>

53:43.470 --> 53:45.431
Petey, am I talking
French here?

53:45.514 --> 53:48.976
Tackle lines up
inside the tight
end, does he not?

53:49.059 --> 53:51.103
It's unbalanced, right?
Do we shift again, Coach?

53:51.186 --> 53:52.813
Yes, they shift.
They all shift.

53:52.896 --> 53:55.107
They have to shift.
They must shift.

53:55.190 --> 53:57.276
Shift, shift, shift.

53:57.359 --> 53:59.528
All right, so you've got
everybody and their dog

53:59.611 --> 54:01.488
shifted over to
the left. Now what?

54:01.572 --> 54:02.823
We are going to run it...

54:02.906 --> 54:04.241
We are going to run it...

54:04.324 --> 54:05.284
...to the right.

54:05.367 --> 54:06.910
...to the right.
To the right, Coach?

54:06.994 --> 54:08.454
But that's away
from our strength.

54:08.537 --> 54:09.788
The weak side of the field.

54:09.872 --> 54:11.790
So, we're going to
run to the weak side?

54:11.874 --> 54:14.418
I like the way that
you think, Mr. Davis.

54:14.501 --> 54:18.672
Gentlemen, when you have
a thoroughbred, you do
not lock him in the barn.

54:18.755 --> 54:20.174
SARETTE: Hut!

54:24.386 --> 54:27.389
I will take one-on-one
out here all day long.

54:47.117 --> 54:49.203
That just might
work, Coach.

54:49.620 --> 54:50.746
Damn right.

54:53.332 --> 54:57.085
"Ernie Davis is a bull-necked,
steel-shouldered running back

54:57.169 --> 55:01.298
"from Syracuse
University, who can run
a football field's length

55:01.381 --> 55:02.674
"in 10 seconds flat."
10 seconds?

55:02.758 --> 55:04.009
Okay, put that
away now, please.

55:04.092 --> 55:05.219
Don't you be modest.

55:05.302 --> 55:06.553
Thank you.
Be proud, Ernie.

55:06.637 --> 55:08.847
You're in the
same magazine
as Reverend King,

55:08.931 --> 55:10.140
that's something.
Yeah.

55:10.224 --> 55:13.810
That is something,
but Sarah, it looks like you
didn't read the best part.

55:13.894 --> 55:17.898
"In his spare time,
the bull-necked Ernie
Davis enjoys sewing,

55:18.315 --> 55:21.401
"baking lasagna,
and writing songs
for his church choir."

55:21.485 --> 55:23.403
Ernie, you never
invite me to church.
Very funny, very funny.

55:23.487 --> 55:25.531
I'm hurt. What is that?
Ernie? Ernie.

55:25.614 --> 55:28.158
Can I have a word
with you, please?

55:29.326 --> 55:30.953
Make me some lasagna.

55:33.455 --> 55:34.831
He can take it.

55:34.915 --> 55:36.708
Good to see you.
JACK: That's Mr. Andreas.

55:36.792 --> 55:38.293
Just turn left there.

55:41.547 --> 55:43.423
(INAUDIBLE)

55:50.180 --> 55:52.808
PREACHER: "He maketh me to
lie down in green pastures.

55:52.891 --> 55:55.852
"He leadeth me
beside the still waters.

55:55.936 --> 55:58.355
"He restoreth my soul.

55:58.438 --> 56:02.734
"He leadeth me in the
paths of righteousness
for his name's sake.

56:02.818 --> 56:05.862
"Yea, though I walk
through the valley
of the shadow of death,

56:05.946 --> 56:09.074
"I will fear no evil,
for thou art with me.

56:09.157 --> 56:11.159
"Thy rod and thy staff..."

56:11.243 --> 56:13.912
40 years,
Pops worked
underground.

56:15.289 --> 56:18.208
Seems wrong
to put him right
back in there.

57:09.051 --> 57:13.555
<i>ANNOUNCER: And the drive
deep into left field.
And it's a home run!</i>

57:33.033 --> 57:36.286
"And his grace
which was bestowed
upon me was not in vain."

57:36.370 --> 57:39.122
<i>YOUNG ERNIE: "His grace
which was bestowed..."</i>

57:39.206 --> 57:42.751
<i>POPS: "... upon me
was not in vain."</i>

57:44.169 --> 57:45.587
(SOBBING)

57:59.101 --> 58:00.227
Pops.

58:01.353 --> 58:05.941
BEN: Now, we barely got
by West Virginia when we
played them here last year,

58:06.024 --> 58:09.486
and they've been
licking their chops
waiting for us ever since.

58:09.569 --> 58:12.280
They play by a
different set of rules.

58:12.614 --> 58:14.449
It will be hostile.

58:15.283 --> 58:17.494
Their fans are unruly,

58:17.786 --> 58:20.914
especially when
they're playing
against a team that

58:20.997 --> 58:23.667
looks a little
different than they do.

58:25.210 --> 58:26.712
Now, load up.

58:41.435 --> 58:42.811
God damn it!

58:43.186 --> 58:45.230
Hey, Squirrel!

58:45.313 --> 58:47.858
Didn't I tell you to
put new laces in these?

58:47.941 --> 58:50.110
I forgot. I'll do it now.

58:50.193 --> 58:51.945
His name is Donald.

58:52.404 --> 58:53.405
What?

58:53.488 --> 58:55.866
His name is Donald.

58:58.076 --> 58:59.661
(LAUGHING)

58:59.745 --> 59:02.831
Hell, Squirrel,
I don't know
which one's worse.

59:03.165 --> 59:08.378
But you see, Davis,
around here, Squirrel
finishes the laces.

59:08.879 --> 59:12.090
If it makes you happy,
you can shine them for me.

59:13.300 --> 59:14.760
PLAYER: Hey, come on!

59:19.473 --> 59:20.891
(WHISTLE BLOWING)
PLAYER: Get him off!

59:21.558 --> 59:24.019
BELL: Hey! Knock it off!

59:24.603 --> 59:26.021
Hey!

59:26.688 --> 59:29.065
What the hell's
going on in here?

59:32.527 --> 59:34.780
Where are you going,
Davis? Davis!

59:34.863 --> 59:36.448
I'm talking to you!

59:36.531 --> 59:39.743
Hey, you guys all saw it.
Coach, he went crazy on me.

59:44.706 --> 59:46.583
BEN: All right,
everyone, listen up.

59:46.666 --> 59:48.960
Everyone is to
keep their helmet
on at all times,

59:49.044 --> 59:50.879
whether you're in
the game or not.

59:50.962 --> 59:53.673
I don't want anyone
hurt by flying bottles.

59:53.757 --> 59:57.052
Davis, Buckley,
Baker, you stay in the
middle of the pack.

59:57.135 --> 59:58.386
Keep your heads down.

59:58.470 --> 01:00:02.015
MAN: It must be Halloween,
'cause here come the spooks!

01:00:02.098 --> 01:00:04.267
We'll be safer
out on the field.

01:00:04.351 --> 01:00:05.477
All right, let's go!

01:00:05.560 --> 01:00:06.895
Come on, boys!
Let's go!

01:00:06.978 --> 01:00:09.189
<i>ANNOUNCER: The unbeaten
Syracuse Orangemen</i>

01:00:09.272 --> 01:00:12.150
<i>have made the journey</i>
<i>to Morgantown, West Virginia.</i>

01:00:12.234 --> 01:00:15.153
<i>They'll face a rugged
Mountaineer team.</i>

01:00:15.237 --> 01:00:16.947
(CROWD BOOING)

01:00:36.675 --> 01:00:40.887
<i>And there's the boot.
Baker takes the football
up to the 20,</i>

01:00:41.263 --> 01:00:46.476
the 30, the 40 and
he's finally brought down
at the 47-yard line.

01:00:46.560 --> 01:00:48.562
Offense, let's go.
Look alive, let's go.

01:00:48.645 --> 01:00:52.399
A full house. 495 dive
on two, on two. Ready?

01:00:52.482 --> 01:00:54.693
PLAYER: Thirty-five,
thirty-five!

01:00:55.443 --> 01:00:56.987
SARETTE: Okie. Okie.

01:00:57.070 --> 01:00:58.530
(ALL BOOING)

01:00:58.613 --> 01:01:00.282
PLAYER: Thirty-five,
thirty-five.

01:01:00.365 --> 01:01:02.659
<i>The Orangemen
break the huddle,
first and 10.</i>

01:01:02.742 --> 01:01:05.495
<i>Out of the full-house
backfield.</i>

01:01:07.455 --> 01:01:11.042
<i>The give is to Ernie Davis.
Davis spins at the line
of scrimmage</i>

01:01:11.126 --> 01:01:14.671
<i>where he's met
by a host of West
Virginia tacklers.</i>

01:01:14.754 --> 01:01:16.298
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

01:01:17.674 --> 01:01:20.051
Get him off him!
Play football!

01:01:23.597 --> 01:01:24.973
REFEREE: Huddle up, 70.

01:01:25.056 --> 01:01:27.809
We will get no justice
from the refs tonight.

01:01:27.893 --> 01:01:30.270
All right, guys.
We're gonna run it
till they stop it.

01:01:30.353 --> 01:01:32.856
Right, full house.
495 dive, on one,
on one. Ready?

01:01:32.939 --> 01:01:34.482
Break!
Break!

01:01:35.233 --> 01:01:40.071
Same play!
Same play! Same hole. Run it.
Same play, same hole, on one.

01:01:40.655 --> 01:01:41.948
Run it.
PLAYER: Strong left!

01:01:42.032 --> 01:01:43.408
Thanks.
PLAYER: Set!

01:01:44.701 --> 01:01:46.953
<i>Second down at
six yards to go.</i>

01:01:47.037 --> 01:01:48.079
SARETTE: Hut one!

01:01:48.163 --> 01:01:52.959
<i>The Orangemen go back to
Ernie Davis. Davis is met
with a wall of Mountaineers.</i>

01:01:54.294 --> 01:01:57.589
And Davis reverses field
with a tremendous move.

01:01:57.672 --> 01:01:59.299
What's he doing?

01:02:09.059 --> 01:02:11.019
<i>Davis picks up a big block</i>

01:02:11.102 --> 01:02:15.023
<i>and with a stiff arm,
gets free into West
Virginia territory.</i>

01:02:18.652 --> 01:02:20.362
Shit, he's going in.

01:02:21.863 --> 01:02:25.951
He's at the 20,
the 10, inside the 5!

01:02:26.034 --> 01:02:27.994
(CROWD BOOING)

01:02:29.079 --> 01:02:30.288
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

01:02:30.830 --> 01:02:32.624
No! Knee down, right here.

01:02:32.707 --> 01:02:35.043
It certainly appeared
from our vantage point here

01:02:35.126 --> 01:02:37.963
that Ernie Davis has
scored on this play.

01:02:38.046 --> 01:02:39.297
REFEREE: I got you
down at the 1.

01:02:39.381 --> 01:02:40.340
You were down!

01:02:40.423 --> 01:02:41.633
No, I got in,
Mr. Official.

01:02:41.716 --> 01:02:42.717
Sir, I got in.
You saw me...

01:02:42.801 --> 01:02:43.969
You want a
penalty, boy?

01:02:44.052 --> 01:02:46.179
Get back in
that huddle now.

01:02:47.806 --> 01:02:48.974
Brokaw, come here!
Yes, Coach.

01:02:49.057 --> 01:02:50.809
Come on, son.
Go get us six. Go!

01:02:50.892 --> 01:02:53.603
Davis, come in!
Come in, son. Come in.

01:02:54.396 --> 01:02:56.147
Come on, son. Let's go.
For me?

01:02:56.231 --> 01:02:57.482
You're holding up
the game. Let's go.
I got it.

01:02:57.565 --> 01:02:59.359
<i>First down Syracuse.</i>

01:03:08.493 --> 01:03:11.454
Why'd you pull me,
Coach? I took it down
there. Let me score.

01:03:11.538 --> 01:03:13.581
If I let you carry
that ball across
the goal line,

01:03:13.665 --> 01:03:17.293
all of us,
we might not get back
on that bus in one piece.

01:03:17.752 --> 01:03:20.547
That's the way they
do things down here.

01:03:21.798 --> 01:03:23.800
<i>Sarette hands off to Brokaw,</i>

01:03:23.883 --> 01:03:25.635
<i>who punches the ball home,</i>

01:03:25.719 --> 01:03:28.638
<i>and the Orangemen
have grabbed a 6-0 lead</i>

01:03:28.722 --> 01:03:31.850
<i>against the Mountaineers
on their own home turf.</i>

01:03:32.434 --> 01:03:33.518
(SIGHS)

01:03:33.601 --> 01:03:34.686
Go home, blackie!

01:03:35.562 --> 01:03:40.442
<i>First down for the Orangemen.
Ball at the West
Virginia 42-yard line.</i>

01:03:42.569 --> 01:03:43.695
<i>Sarette with the fake.</i>

01:03:43.778 --> 01:03:48.616
<i>Ernie Davis across the left
side breaks the tackle and
gets into the open field.</i>

01:03:56.458 --> 01:03:58.376
BEN: Good run! Good run!

01:03:58.460 --> 01:04:00.420
Brokaw, come here.
Yeah, Coach.

01:04:00.503 --> 01:04:03.214
Strong right,
fullback wedge
eight. Go!

01:04:03.298 --> 01:04:04.799
Ernie, Ernie!

01:04:07.802 --> 01:04:09.637
Brokaw, get in there!

01:04:10.805 --> 01:04:12.640
Right full house, 40 broom.
On one, on one. Ready.

01:04:12.724 --> 01:04:14.142
Break!
Break!

01:04:14.225 --> 01:04:16.352
<i>SIMMONS: Davis,
get off the field.</i>

01:04:16.436 --> 01:04:19.147
<i>WILL: Now, you got a white man
telling you what you can
and can't do...</i>

01:04:19.230 --> 01:04:21.566
<i>...one hundred years
away from here...</i>

01:04:21.649 --> 01:04:22.984
Ref, time out. Time out.

01:04:23.068 --> 01:04:24.277
You don't have any more.

01:04:24.360 --> 01:04:25.862
<i>MAN: We are still not yet...</i>

01:04:25.945 --> 01:04:27.155
You're just his
educated nigger.

01:04:30.033 --> 01:04:32.410
<i>They gonna be
looking up to you.</i>

01:04:33.244 --> 01:04:36.664
I think you owe them more
than just running a ball.

01:04:43.379 --> 01:04:45.006
(CROWD EXCLAIMS)

01:04:52.347 --> 01:04:53.848
(CROWD BOOING)

01:05:06.945 --> 01:05:08.321
What the hell do you
think you're doing?

01:05:08.404 --> 01:05:11.157
What did I tell you
about the rules down here?

01:05:11.282 --> 01:05:13.201
What are you...
We just scored.
Bullshit.

01:05:13.284 --> 01:05:16.079
You scored!
We're a team.
I'm the coach.

01:05:16.162 --> 01:05:18.957
You're a goddamn running
back. You're my goddamn
running back,

01:05:19.040 --> 01:05:22.127
and you will do
what I tell you,
when I tell you to do it.

01:05:22.210 --> 01:05:25.046
Now, you plant your ass
down on that bench.

01:05:43.273 --> 01:05:44.899
Am I invisible?

01:05:45.358 --> 01:05:47.277
What?
Am I invisible to you?

01:05:47.360 --> 01:05:51.573
Am I an X, an O in your
goddamn playbook, or do you
see a person standing here?

01:05:51.656 --> 01:05:54.409
Am I Avatus Stone?
Am I Jim Brown?

01:05:54.868 --> 01:05:56.286
Just a running back?
That's bullshit!

01:05:56.369 --> 01:05:57.704
You're about
this close, Davis.

01:05:57.787 --> 01:05:59.164
Come on, let's go.

01:05:59.247 --> 01:06:01.541
You know, maybe,
just maybe, Coach,

01:06:01.624 --> 01:06:04.085
the rules down here
are your rules, too.

01:06:04.169 --> 01:06:05.753
That's enough.
Come on.

01:06:39.954 --> 01:06:40.997
What?

01:06:42.749 --> 01:06:44.167
You all right?

01:06:47.754 --> 01:06:48.796
Yeah.

01:06:53.176 --> 01:06:54.552
Good game.

01:06:58.806 --> 01:07:00.558
Good game, Ben.
Mike?

01:07:00.642 --> 01:07:01.643
I tried not to
run up the score.

01:07:01.726 --> 01:07:04.562
I know. You just had
our number tonight.

01:07:04.646 --> 01:07:08.066
Say, Ben, how many coloreds
you got playing for you?

01:07:08.149 --> 01:07:09.192
Three, why?

01:07:09.275 --> 01:07:11.527
You just be careful, Ben.
They got no discipline.

01:07:11.611 --> 01:07:15.156
Too many of them
and they'll take
the team away from you.

01:07:15.949 --> 01:07:17.617
Now, you give my
best to Reggie.

01:07:17.700 --> 01:07:19.160
Coon-lover!

01:07:51.442 --> 01:07:53.027
Can I sit down?

01:08:06.708 --> 01:08:08.835
I'm sorry I lost my temper.

01:08:10.920 --> 01:08:14.132
But I'm not sorry
I stayed in the game,
and I'm not sorry I scored.

01:08:14.215 --> 01:08:16.050
Now, what kind of
an apology is this?

01:08:16.134 --> 01:08:19.053
I've never walked off
the field for anybody.

01:08:19.595 --> 01:08:20.805
(SIGHS)

01:08:20.888 --> 01:08:23.390
These people down
here, they're dug in.

01:08:23.474 --> 01:08:24.725
They're set in their
ways. We got...

01:08:24.809 --> 01:08:25.810
Coach, that...

01:08:25.893 --> 01:08:27.395
You're just hiding
behind those words.

01:08:27.478 --> 01:08:28.979
I have a responsibility
to my team, Davis.

01:08:29.063 --> 01:08:30.606
That's not how
it has to be.

01:08:30.689 --> 01:08:34.068
Yes. Jack, Art and me,
we're all a part of your team.

01:08:34.986 --> 01:08:38.781
But we can't run
across that goal line
down here without you.

01:08:40.783 --> 01:08:44.078
It doesn't mean a damn
thing unless you're with us.

01:08:48.082 --> 01:08:49.459
Is that it?

01:08:51.877 --> 01:08:53.087
(SIGHS)

01:09:11.522 --> 01:09:13.691
<i>ANNOUNCER 1: And in</i>
<i>college football,</i>
<i>the Syracuse Orangemen</i>

01:09:13.774 --> 01:09:17.569
<i>continue their dominance
of the Eastern Conference
with a 29-0...</i>

01:09:17.653 --> 01:09:19.697
<i>ANNOUNCER 2: Fans,
I wish all of you
could be here</i>

01:09:19.781 --> 01:09:22.116
<i>to see what these eyes
have just witnessed.</i>

01:09:22.200 --> 01:09:26.371
<i>...brilliant</i>
<i>displays of athletic talent
I've seen on any gridiron.</i>

01:09:26.453 --> 01:09:28.622
Come on, guys!
Sustain your block!

01:09:28.706 --> 01:09:31.834
<i>...led by Ernie Davis,
from Elmira, New York.</i>

01:09:31.917 --> 01:09:34.504
<i>ANNOUNCER 3: Another
jaw-dropping performance here
at Navy Memorial Stadium.</i>

01:09:34.587 --> 01:09:37.840
<i>ANNOUNCER 2: I tell you
one thing, he's electrified
this crowd.</i>

01:09:38.800 --> 01:09:41.511
<i>The unbeaten
Syracuse Orangemen...</i>

01:09:41.594 --> 01:09:43.220
<i>ANNOUNCER 4: Davis,
who has been</i>

01:09:43.304 --> 01:09:47.600
<i>nothing short of brilliant
today, reserves the victory</i>

01:09:47.683 --> 01:09:51.229
<i>for coach Ben Schwartzwalder
and the Syracuse Orangemen.</i>

01:09:51.312 --> 01:09:52.647
ALL: (SINGING) <i>...nothing
but a hound dog</i>

01:09:52.729 --> 01:09:53.898
You know it!

01:09:53.981 --> 01:09:56.401
<i>Crying all the time</i>

01:09:57.902 --> 01:10:01.114
<i>Well, you ain't never
caught a rabbit</i>

01:10:01.197 --> 01:10:04.617
<i>And you ain't no
friend of mine</i>

01:10:04.700 --> 01:10:05.993
(ALL CHEERING)

01:10:06.494 --> 01:10:08.162
SIMMONS: Settle down.
Listen up, boys.

01:10:08.246 --> 01:10:10.540
All right, listen up.
Listen up!

01:10:10.623 --> 01:10:11.833
PLAYER: Coach!

01:10:15.253 --> 01:10:18.131
Gentlemen,
congratulations.

01:10:19.090 --> 01:10:22.093
Undefeated with
a number one ranking
is something to be proud of.

01:10:22.176 --> 01:10:23.678
ALL: Yeah!

01:10:23.761 --> 01:10:24.762
But...

01:10:25.471 --> 01:10:26.514
But...

01:10:27.390 --> 01:10:30.017
Mr. Andreas
has informed me

01:10:30.476 --> 01:10:33.312
that we have been offered
two different bowl games,

01:10:33.396 --> 01:10:35.440
the Orange Bowl in Miami

01:10:35.982 --> 01:10:38.192
and the Cotton
Bowl in Dallas.

01:10:38.526 --> 01:10:42.530
Now, in Miami,
we would play Georgia,
ranked ninth in the polls.

01:10:42.822 --> 01:10:48.494
And in Dallas, we would
play Texas, ranked second,
right behind us.

01:10:49.829 --> 01:10:55.334
If we win either
game, we will be
the national champions.

01:10:56.169 --> 01:10:59.505
Texas is the tougher
opponent, the tougher team.

01:11:00.381 --> 01:11:04.594
But to be the best,
I believe you have
to beat the best.

01:11:07.597 --> 01:11:11.726
So,I guess you
know how I would vote,
but this is your vote.

01:11:13.060 --> 01:11:16.522
This is your team.
Your decision.

01:11:21.944 --> 01:11:23.112
Texas.

01:11:26.407 --> 01:11:27.909
PLAYER 1: Texas.

01:11:28.284 --> 01:11:29.827
PLAYER 2:Texas.

01:11:29.911 --> 01:11:31.204
PLAYER 3: Texas.

01:11:31.287 --> 01:11:32.497
Texas.
Texas.

01:11:32.580 --> 01:11:33.748
Texas.
Texas.

01:11:33.831 --> 01:11:34.957
ALL: Texas.

01:11:35.041 --> 01:11:36.083
Texas.

01:11:36.167 --> 01:11:37.251
Texas.

01:11:37.376 --> 01:11:39.086
Texas.

01:11:39.170 --> 01:11:41.047
Looking forward to it!
Texas.

01:11:41.130 --> 01:11:42.340
Texas.
Texas!

01:11:42.423 --> 01:11:44.008
Texas.
Texas.

01:11:44.091 --> 01:11:45.259
Texas.

01:11:51.766 --> 01:11:53.643
A lot of people think
the Texas Longhorns

01:11:53.768 --> 01:11:55.645
are the best team
in the nation.

01:11:55.728 --> 01:11:57.438
One big reason is Clay Taylor.

01:11:57.522 --> 01:12:00.066
Ail-American,
best Division One tackle
in the nation

01:12:00.149 --> 01:12:02.360
three years in a row.

01:12:05.404 --> 01:12:09.200
Now, some folks even think
that the only reason
that we are undefeated

01:12:09.283 --> 01:12:12.828
is because we have not met
Clay Taylor and his teammates.

01:12:14.539 --> 01:12:18.084
I want everyone to
take a good long look
at what we're up against here

01:12:18.167 --> 01:12:21.379
because in Texas,
football is a religion.

01:12:29.303 --> 01:12:31.973
You think we been south?

01:12:32.056 --> 01:12:34.308
We ain't been south
till we go to Texas.

01:12:55.580 --> 01:12:57.123
Schwedes,
give me a goose-step.

01:12:57.206 --> 01:12:59.292
(ALL LAUGHING)

01:13:14.849 --> 01:13:18.644
<i>FAUBUS ON TV:</i>
<i>We are now faced</i>
<i>with a far different problem.</i>

01:13:18.728 --> 01:13:23.107
<i>The forcible integration
of the public schools
of Little Rock</i>

01:13:23.190 --> 01:13:27.862
<i>against</i>
<i>the overwhelming sentiment
of the people of the area.</i>

01:13:38.372 --> 01:13:40.082
<i>CROWD: Two, four, six, eight!</i>

01:13:40.166 --> 01:13:41.834
<i>We don't want to integrate!</i>

01:13:42.126 --> 01:13:43.711
<i>Two, four, six, eight!</i>

01:13:43.794 --> 01:13:45.713
<i>We don't want to integrate!</i>

01:13:48.883 --> 01:13:50.134
(BUS HORN HONKING)

01:14:01.437 --> 01:14:03.773
<i>KING: We still have
the attitude of love,</i>

01:14:03.856 --> 01:14:08.611
we <i>still have the method
of passive resistance</i>

01:14:08.694 --> 01:14:11.947
<i>and we are still
insisting emphatically,</i>

01:14:12.031 --> 01:14:14.617
<i>that violence is
self-defeating.</i>

01:14:14.992 --> 01:14:18.037
<i>That he who</i>
<i>lives by the sword</i>
<i>will perish by the sword.</i>

01:14:25.503 --> 01:14:27.630
(SIREN BLARING)

01:14:28.673 --> 01:14:31.258
(ALL CLAMORING)

01:14:43.229 --> 01:14:44.814
This is quite a ruckus.

01:14:44.897 --> 01:14:46.774
Hey, Ernie,
Roger Page, Channel Nine.

01:14:46.857 --> 01:14:48.818
They're calling this game
the North against the South.

01:14:48.901 --> 01:14:50.695
In light of what's
going on in this country,

01:14:50.778 --> 01:14:53.030
do you feel added pressure
to represent change?

01:14:53.114 --> 01:14:56.200
We don't concern
ourselves with politics.

01:14:56.283 --> 01:14:58.744
We're just here to
play a great football game

01:14:59.161 --> 01:15:00.246
and take home
the championship.

01:15:00.329 --> 01:15:02.581
To be honest, Mr. Page,
when I'm out on that field,

01:15:02.665 --> 01:15:05.292
I only think about
winning the game.

01:15:05.876 --> 01:15:09.630
But that doesn't mean
I don't know
the color of my own skin.

01:15:12.341 --> 01:15:14.009
Let's check in.

01:15:19.014 --> 01:15:20.725
We've got a problem, Ben.

01:15:20.850 --> 01:15:21.976
What?

01:15:22.143 --> 01:15:26.021
The Aristocrat Hotel
does not allow coloreds
to stay here.

01:15:27.732 --> 01:15:29.900
I need my team together, Lew.

01:15:29.984 --> 01:15:33.154
Now, you do whatever it takes
to make that happen.

01:15:33.487 --> 01:15:36.407
What's the problem?
What's the problem here?

01:15:41.954 --> 01:15:44.039
Right this way, gentlemen.

01:15:49.920 --> 01:15:51.130
(COUGHS)

01:15:51.464 --> 01:15:54.884
Fellas,
looks like we once again
found the Negro wing.

01:16:01.515 --> 01:16:02.516
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

01:16:02.600 --> 01:16:04.185
State seven!
State seven!

